---
import LocationHubTemplate from '@/components/LocationHubTemplate.astro';
import CalloutBox from '@/components/CalloutBox.astro';
import CashOfferCard from '@/components/CashOfferCard.astro';
import { getCountiesByState, getCountyBySlug } from '@/data/counties';
import { cityUrl, countyUrl } from '@/lib/urls';
import { brand } from '@/data/brand';

export function getStaticPaths() {
  return getCountiesByState('ks').map((c) => ({
    params: { county: c.slug },
    props: { county: c },
  }));
}

const { county } = Astro.props;
const stateAbbr = 'KS';
const stateName = 'Kansas';
const stateSlug = 'ks';

// Build children (cities) for the LocationHubTemplate
const children = county.cities.map((c) => ({
  name: c.name,
  href: cityUrl(stateSlug, county.slug, c.slug),
  subtitle: `${c.neighborhoods.length} neighborhoods | Median: ${c.medianHomeValue}`,
  description: c.description,
}));

// Quick facts for sidebar
const facts = [
  { label: 'County Seat', value: county.seatCity },
  { label: 'Population', value: county.population },
  { label: 'Median Home Value', value: county.medianHomeValue, color: 'red' as const },
  { label: 'Cities Served', value: `${county.cities.length}` },
  { label: 'Our Offer', value: 'Within 24 hours', color: 'green' as const },
  { label: 'Your Repair Cost', value: '$0', color: 'green' as const },
];

// County pills (other counties in same state)
const countyPills = getCountiesByState(stateSlug)
  .filter((c) => c.slug !== county.slug)
  .map((c) => ({ label: c.name, href: countyUrl(stateSlug, c.slug) }));

// Related links
const relatedLinks = [
  { label: 'Tax-Delinquent Properties', href: '/tax-delinquent/' },
  { label: 'Probate Guide', href: '/probate/' },
  { label: 'Pre-Foreclosure', href: '/situations/pre-foreclosure/' },
  { label: 'Inherited Property', href: '/situations/inherited-property/' },
  { label: 'Behind on Payments', href: '/situations/behind-on-payments/' },
];

const breadcrumbs = [
  { label: stateName, href: `/${stateSlug}/` },
  { label: `${county.name}` },
];

const title = `Navigating ${county.name} Distressed Property: Your 2026 Guide to Probate, Tax Delinquency, and Redemption`;
const description = `Navigating Probate, Tax Delinquency, and Redemption in ${county.name}, ${stateName}. Expert guidance for distressed property owners across ${county.cities.length} cities.`;
const shortAnswer = `Whether you're navigating probate through the ${county.probateCourtName}, facing a judicial tax foreclosure under K.S.A. 79-2801, or trying to understand your rights before a sheriff's sale in ${county.name} — you have options. We help ${county.name} property owners resolve distressed situations with fair cash offers, no repairs, and closings as fast as 7 days.`;

const heroSubtitle = `${county.name} property owners facing probate through the ${county.probateCourtName}, judicial tax foreclosure with a ${county.taxSaleMonth} sheriff's sale, or pre-sale redemption questions under K.S.A. 79-2801 — we've helped families in your exact situation. Our office is ${county.courthouse.distanceMiles} miles from the ${county.courthouse.name} at ${county.courthouse.address}. K.S.A. Chapter 59 governs probate; K.S.A. 79-2801 governs tax foreclosure. We know both.`;

const heroStats = [
  {
    icon: `<svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M3 9l9-7 9 7v11a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2z"/><polyline points="9 22 9 12 15 12 15 22"/></svg>`,
    number: '47+',
    label: 'Happy Sellers Helped',
  },
  {
    icon: `<svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><polyline points="12 6 12 12 16 14"/></svg>`,
    number: '11+',
    label: 'Years Serving KC Metro',
  },
  {
    icon: `<svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><rect x="3" y="4" width="18" height="18" rx="2" ry="2"/><line x1="16" y1="2" x2="16" y2="6"/><line x1="8" y1="2" x2="8" y2="6"/><line x1="3" y1="10" x2="21" y2="10"/></svg>`,
    number: '15 Day',
    label: 'Average Closing',
  },
];

// Build contact items from courthouse data
const contactItems = [
  { label: 'Office', value: county.courthouse.name },
  { label: 'Phone', value: county.courthouse.phone, href: `tel:${county.courthouse.phone.replace(/[^0-9]/g, '')}` },
  { label: 'Address', value: county.courthouse.address },
  { label: 'Website', value: county.courthouse.website.replace('https://', '').replace('http://', ''), href: county.courthouse.website },
];

// Collect neighborhood distress data for the county page
const distressCards = county.cities.slice(0, 3).flatMap((c) =>
  c.neighborhoods.slice(0, 2).map((n) => ({
    neighborhood: n.name,
    city: c.name,
    factors: n.distressFactors,
    hook: n.localHook,
  }))
);

// Tax sale countdown
const taxSaleDate = new Date(county.taxSaleDate2026 + 'T10:00:00');
const today = new Date();
const daysUntilSale = Math.ceil((taxSaleDate.getTime() - today.getTime()) / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24));
const taxSaleDateFormatted = taxSaleDate.toLocaleDateString('en-US', { weekday: 'long', year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' });

const jumpPills = [
  { href: '#probate-help', label: 'Probate / Inherited', desc: 'Sell inherited property during or after probate', color: '#3B82F6' },
  { href: '#tax-delinquent-solutions', label: 'Back Taxes', desc: 'Resolve delinquent property taxes before sale', color: '#CC0000' },
  { href: '#tax-redemption-rights', label: 'Tax Redemption', desc: 'Understand your rights before sheriff\'s sale', color: '#D97706' },
  { href: '#county-resources', label: 'Courthouse & Resources', desc: 'County offices, contacts, and directions', color: '#6366F1' },
  { href: '#process', label: 'Get Your Offer', desc: '4-step process from call to cash in hand', color: '#16A34A' },
  { href: '#how-we-help', label: 'How Saving KC Helps', desc: `Our process for ${county.name} property owners`, color: '#9333EA' },
];
---

<LocationHubTemplate
  title={title}
  description={description}
  shortAnswer={shortAnswer}
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  children={children}
  facts={facts}
  locationName={`${county.name}`}
  contactItems={contactItems}
  countyPills={countyPills}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  canonical={`${brand.domain}/${stateSlug}/${county.slug}/`}
  countyFaqs={county.countyFaqs}
  courthouseName={county.courthouse.name}
  courthouseAddress={county.courthouse.address}
  courthouseWebsite={county.courthouse.website}
  heroStats={heroStats}
  heroSubtitle={heroSubtitle}
  heroHighlight=""
  heroGreenText={county.name}
  state="ks"
>
  <!-- STICKY JUMP BAR -->
  <nav class="jump-bar jump-bar--sticky" id="jump-bar-primary">
    <span class="jump-bar__title">What Do You Need Help With Today?</span>
    <div class="jump-bar__links">{jumpPills.map((p) => (<a href={p.href} class="jump-bar__link" style={`--jb-color: ${p.color}`}>{p.label}</a>))}</div>
  </nav>

  <!-- ENTITY PROXIMITY SECTION -->
  <section class="content-section" id="entity-connection">
    <h2>Local Expertise Near the {county.name} Courthouse</h2>
    <p class="answer-block">
      <span class="answer-date">Updated March 2026</span>
      Saving KC Homebuyers operates from 1705 Baltimore Ave in Kansas City — {county.courthouse.distanceMiles} miles from the {county.courthouse.name} at {county.courthouse.address}. We file documents, attend hearings, and close transactions through local title companies in {county.seatCity} multiple times a week. Call <a href="tel:8164292900">(816) 429-2900</a>.
    </p>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>
        {county.narrativeHook}
      </p>
      <p>
        This proximity ensures faster document filing for probate cases and quicker title searches for tax-delinquent properties. When a sheriff's sale deadline is measured in days — not weeks — having boots on the ground at the {county.courthouse.name} matters. We know the recording timelines, the staff at the register of deeds, and the title companies that specialize in distressed closings in {county.seatCity}.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <nav class="jump-bar">
    <span class="jump-bar__title">What would you like help on?</span>
    <div class="jump-bar__links">{jumpPills.map((p) => (<a href={p.href} class="jump-bar__link" style={`--jb-color: ${p.color}`}>{p.label}</a>))}</div>
  </nav>

  <!-- SECTION 1: PROBATE -->
  <section class="content-section" id="probate-help">
    <h2>How Do I Sell Inherited Property in {county.name}?</h2>
    <p class="answer-block">
      <span class="answer-date">Updated March 2026</span>
      Yes, you can sell inherited property in Kansas without waiting for probate to close. If a transfer-on-death deed was filed, you can sell immediately after recording the transfer. Otherwise, the {county.probateCourtName} oversees proceedings that typically take 6 to 12 months — but selling during probate is allowed with court approval. To bypass repairs and long listing times, contact Saving KC at <a href="tel:8164292900">(816) 429-2900</a> for a direct cash offer while the estate is still open.
    </p>
    <a href="/get-offer/" class="inline-cta">Get My Cash Offer →</a>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>
        Losing a loved one is hard enough without the added weight of an inherited property you're not sure what to do with. If you're now facing decisions about a home in {county.name}, know that you don't have to figure it all out at once. Whether you're weeks into the grief or months into the process, your options remain open.
      </p>
      <p>
        We're here to help you understand them without pressure. Call us at <a href="tel:8164292900">816-429-2900</a> to discuss your inherited property.
      </p>
      <p>
        Kansas probate works differently from Missouri, and it's worth understanding how. Kansas courts offer both supervised and unsupervised administration of estates. Unsupervised administration is far more common — under this process, the personal representative (the executor) has broad authority to act on behalf of the estate without seeking court approval at every step.
      </p>
      <p>
        Once the {county.probateCourtName} issues Letters Testamentary, the personal representative can sign contracts, list the property, and accept offers — all without waiting for the estate to formally close.
      </p>
      <CalloutBox
        variant="blue"
        title="KANSAS PROBATE: SUPERVISED VS. UNSUPERVISED"
        text={`<strong>Unsupervised administration</strong> (most common) gives the personal representative broad authority to sell property without court approval at every step. <strong>Supervised administration</strong> requires court approval for each transaction — adding time and cost. Ask your attorney which applies to your ${county.name} estate.`}
      />
      <p>
        {county.probateInfo}
      </p>
      <h3>Kansas Transfer-on-Death (TOD) Deeds</h3>
      <CalloutBox
        variant="yellow"
        title="TRANSFER-ON-DEATH DEED"
        text={`Kansas offers TOD deeds that bypass probate entirely. If the deceased owner filed a TOD deed with the ${county.name} Register of Deeds, the named beneficiary receives the property automatically upon the owner's death. Have a TOD deed? You can sell to us as soon as the transfer is recorded — often within days of receiving the death certificate. No probate, no court approval, no waiting. <a href="tel:8164292900">Call 816-429-2900</a>.`}
      />
      <p>
        If the estate's gross value is $40,000 or less, Kansas allows a simplified procedure. You can file a petition with the {county.probateCourtName} for summary administration, which significantly reduces the timeline and cost compared to full probate.
      </p>
      <p>
        Full probate in {county.name} typically takes 6 to 12 months — generally faster than Missouri. Filing fees run $50 to $200. Attorney fees range from $1,500 to $4,000 depending on complexity. During this period, you're still responsible for property taxes, insurance, and maintenance on a property that may be sitting vacant.
      </p>
      <p>
        You don't need to wait for the estate to close. Kansas law allows the personal representative to sell real property during probate with court approval. Whether probate is complete, in progress, or hasn't been filed yet, you have options. We buy inherited properties at any stage — you don't need to clean out, repair, or even visit the property.
      </p>
    </div>
    <CalloutBox
      variant="green"
      title="SELLING IS AN OPTION"
      text={`You don't have to wait for probate to close, a TOD deed to be recorded, or the estate to be settled. We buy inherited properties in ${county.name} at any stage — as-is, no cleaning, no repairs. <a href="tel:8164292900">Call 816-429-2900</a> to discuss your situation.`}
    />

    <!-- Probate Timeline -->
    <h3>Kansas Probate Timeline</h3>
    <div class="process-timeline">
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">1</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">Death of Property Owner</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">Check for a transfer-on-death (TOD) deed first — if filed, the beneficiary receives the property automatically under K.S.A. Chapter 59. No probate needed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">2</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">File Probate with {county.probateCourtName}</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">If no TOD deed exists, submit the will and petition. Kansas courts typically assign unsupervised administration, giving the personal representative broad authority.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">3</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">Receive Letters Testamentary</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">Court issues authority to act on behalf of the estate. Under unsupervised administration, you can sell property without seeking court approval for each transaction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">4</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">Sell Property (During Probate)</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">You don't have to wait for the estate to close. With Letters Testamentary, you can accept a cash offer and close on your timeline.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">5</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">Close Estate</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">Final accounting, distribute remaining assets, and close the estate. Kansas probate typically takes 6–12 months — faster than Missouri.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <CalloutBox
      type="info"
      title={`${county.name.toUpperCase()} PROBATE COURT`}
      text={`Probate cases in ${county.name} are handled by the ${county.probateCourtName}, located at ${county.courthouse.address}. Our office is ${county.courthouse.distanceMiles} miles away — we work with this court regularly and can coordinate with your attorney to close as soon as the court allows.`}
    />
  </section>

  <nav class="jump-bar">
    <span class="jump-bar__title">What would you like help on?</span>
    <div class="jump-bar__links">{jumpPills.map((p) => (<a href={p.href} class="jump-bar__link" style={`--jb-color: ${p.color}`}>{p.label}</a>))}</div>
  </nav>

  <!-- SECTION 2: TAX DELINQUENT -->
  <section class="content-section" id="tax-delinquent-solutions">
    <h2>What Happens When You Owe Back Taxes in {county.name}?</h2>
    <p class="answer-block">
      <span class="answer-date">Updated March 2026</span>
      Your property faces judicial tax foreclosure if taxes remain unpaid past December 20. Under K.S.A. 79-2801, Kansas counties file suit in district court — not a lien sale. In {county.name}, the sheriff's sale typically occurs in {county.taxSaleMonth}. Your right to redeem ends the day before the sheriff's sale. Once the sheriff's deed is issued, ownership transfers permanently with no post-sale redemption. If you are behind on taxes, Saving KC (<a href="tel:8164292900">816-429-2900</a>) can clear your debt at closing, allowing you to walk away with your remaining equity.
    </p>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>
        If you've missed your {county.name} property tax payment, the clock started the moment the December 20 deadline passed — and Kansas moves faster than most homeowners expect. Unlike Missouri, which gives until December 31, Kansas counties begin enforcement earlier. Penalties accrue immediately. By {county.taxSaleMonth}, delinquent properties in {county.name} are eligible for judicial foreclosure under K.S.A. 79-2801, and once that process begins, your options narrow quickly.
      </p>
      <p>
        {county.taxLienInfo}
      </p>
      <p>
        Kansas reassesses property values {county.reassessmentCycle}, which means your tax bill can change every year even if you've made no improvements. If rising assessments have pushed your tax burden beyond what you can manage, selling eliminates that obligation entirely.
      </p>
      <CalloutBox
        variant="red"
        title="KANSAS HAS NO POST-SALE REDEMPTION"
        text={`Unlike Missouri's 1-year redemption window, Kansas uses <strong>judicial tax foreclosure</strong> under K.S.A. 79-2801. Your right to pay and stop the sale ends the <strong>day before the sheriff's sale</strong>. Once the sheriff's deed is recorded, ownership transfers permanently. No second chance.`}
      />
      <p>
        Here's how it works: when taxes go unpaid, the county attorney files a foreclosure action in district court. The court enters a judgment and orders a sheriff's sale. You may redeem the property by paying all delinquent taxes, interest, and costs — but that right expires the day before the sheriff's sale. Once the sheriff's deed is issued, ownership transfers permanently.
      </p>
      <p>
        You don't need to pay off back taxes before selling. At closing, the title company uses the sale proceeds to clear all delinquent taxes, mechanic's liens, and judgment liens. If your equity exceeds what you owe, you walk away with the remaining balance — and a clean break from the property. Even if the taxes are significant, selling before the sheriff's sale is almost always better than losing the property entirely through foreclosure.
      </p>
    </div>
    <h3>2026 Tax Foreclosure Critical Dates</h3>
    <div class="countdown-banner">
      <div class="countdown-banner__icon">
        <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><polyline points="12 6 12 12 16 14"/></svg>
      </div>
      <div class="countdown-banner__text">
        {daysUntilSale > 0
          ? <><strong>{daysUntilSale} days</strong> until the {county.name} tax foreclosure sale — <strong>{taxSaleDateFormatted}</strong></>
          : <><strong>The 2026 {county.name} tax foreclosure sale has passed.</strong></>
        }
      </div>
      <div class="countdown-banner__pattern">{county.taxSalePattern}</div>
    </div>
    {county.delinquentPropertyCount2026 && (
      <div class="auction-watch">
        <div class="auction-watch__badge">2026 AUCTION WATCH</div>
        <div class="auction-watch__body">
          <strong>{county.delinquentPropertyCount2026} properties</strong> are currently on the {county.name} delinquent tax list for the upcoming sheriff's sale.
          {county.delinquentListUrl && (
            <a href={county.delinquentListUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="auction-watch__link">View the county list →</a>
          )}
        </div>
      </div>
    )}
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>DETAIL</th>
          <th>INFORMATION</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Recurring Schedule</td>
          <td><strong>{county.taxSalePattern}</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>2026 Sale Date</td>
          <td><strong>{taxSaleDateFormatted}</strong></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Judicial Foreclosure Sale</td>
          <td>{county.taxSaleDates}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Sale Location</td>
          <td>{county.taxSaleLocation}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Annual Tax Deadline</td>
          <td>{county.taxDeadline}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Redemption Deadline</td>
          <td>Day before the sheriff's sale — no redemption rights after sale</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <!-- Tax Foreclosure Timeline -->
    <h3>{county.name} Tax Foreclosure Timeline</h3>
    <div class="process-timeline">
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">1</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">December 20 — Tax Due Date</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">Kansas property taxes are due December 20 (earlier than Missouri's December 31). Miss this date and penalties start immediately.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">2</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">Judicial Foreclosure Filed</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">The county attorney files a foreclosure action in district court under K.S.A. 79-2801. The court enters a judgment and orders a sheriff's sale.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">3</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">{county.taxSaleMonth} — Sheriff's Sale</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">Your property is sold at sheriff's sale. Your right to redeem expires the day before the sale — not after.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="process-timeline__step">
        <span class="process-timeline__number">4</span>
        <div class="process-timeline__title">No Post-Sale Redemption</div>
        <p class="process-timeline__desc">Unlike Missouri's 1-year window, Kansas has NO redemption period after the sheriff's sale. Once the sheriff's deed records, ownership is gone permanently.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <CalloutBox
      variant="gray"
      text={`Every month you wait, the judgment grows and the sheriff's sale gets closer. Kansas uses judicial tax foreclosure — there is no redemption period after the sale. Once the sheriff's deed records, ownership is gone permanently. Selling your ${county.name} property now clears all tax debt at closing and puts remaining equity in your hands. <a href="tel:8164292900">Call Ernest: 816-429-2900</a>.`}
    />
    <CalloutBox
      type="fact"
      title={`${county.name.toUpperCase()} TAX DEADLINE`}
      text={`Your ${county.name} property tax is due ${county.taxDeadline}. Delinquent properties face judicial foreclosure under K.S.A. 79-2801 with a sheriff's sale typically in ${county.taxSaleMonth}. There is no redemption after the sale — if you're behind, selling before the sheriff's sale is your only option to preserve equity. We can close in as few as 7 days.`}
    />
  </section>

  <nav class="jump-bar">
    <span class="jump-bar__title">What would you like help on?</span>
    <div class="jump-bar__links">{jumpPills.map((p) => (<a href={p.href} class="jump-bar__link" style={`--jb-color: ${p.color}`}>{p.label}</a>))}</div>
  </nav>

  <!-- SECTION 3: TAX FORECLOSURE RIGHTS -->
  <section class="content-section" id="tax-redemption-rights">
    <h2>What Are My Rights Before a {county.name} Sheriff's Sale?</h2>
    <p class="answer-block">
      <span class="answer-date">Updated March 2026</span>
      Under Kansas judicial tax foreclosure (K.S.A. 79-2801), you have the right to pay all delinquent taxes, interest, and court costs to stop the foreclosure — but only before the sheriff's sale. Once the sheriff's sale occurs and a sheriff's deed is issued, your ownership is extinguished permanently. There is no post-sale redemption in Kansas. If your deadline is approaching, contact Saving KC at <a href="tel:8164292900">(816) 429-2900</a> immediately to see if a same-day buyout is possible.
    </p>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>
        Kansas judicial tax foreclosure under K.S.A. 79-2801 works differently from Missouri's system. In Kansas, the county attorney files a court action, the district court enters a foreclosure judgment, and a sheriff's sale is ordered. Before that sale occurs, you can stop the foreclosure by paying all delinquent taxes, accrued interest, penalties, and court costs. Your right to pay and stop the sale expires the day before the sheriff's sale. Once the sale takes place and a sheriff's deed is recorded, ownership transfers permanently. There is no grace period, no post-sale redemption window, and no court process to reclaim the property after the deed issues.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>The Foreclosure Math</h3>
    <CalloutBox
      variant="yellow"
      title="WHAT YOU OWE TO STOP THE SALE"
      text={`To stop a Kansas judicial tax foreclosure on your ${county.name} property, you must pay <strong>all of the following</strong> before the day of the sheriff's sale:<br/><br/><strong>1. All delinquent taxes</strong> — every dollar owed across all delinquent years.<br/><strong>2. Accrued interest and penalties</strong> — compounding from the original December 20 due date.<br/><strong>3. All court costs</strong> — filing fees, service of process, and county attorney fees.<br/><br/>Unlike Missouri, Kansas has <strong>no post-sale redemption</strong>. Once the sheriff's deed records, ownership is gone permanently. On a ${county.medianHomeValue} home with 2–3 years of back taxes, the total payoff can exceed $10,000. If you can't cover that lump sum, selling to Saving KC clears the debt at closing and preserves your remaining equity. <a href="tel:8164292900">Call (816) 429-2900</a>.`}
    />

    <div class="section-body">
      <p>
        Here's a complication most homeowners miss: if there's a pending probate on the property, the judicial foreclosure proceeds concurrently with estate administration. The probate court will not pause the sheriff's sale while the estate is being settled. Neither the estate nor the heir may be able to act fast enough when both processes run simultaneously. In these situations, selling before the sheriff's sale is often the only path to preserving any equity in the property.
